k"},"en":{"1008–1090":"1008–1090","1005–1040":"1005–1040","1030–1086":"1030–1086","1092–Male":"1092–Deceased","1008":"1008","ABT 1030":"about 1030","1090":"1090","ABT 1086":"about 1086","1005":"1005","1034":"1034","1086":"1086","1030":"1030","1040":"1040","1092":"1092","Cathédrale Notre-Dame de Rouen, Rouen, Departement de la Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, France":"Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France","Amfreville-, Sur-Iton, Bailiwick Rouen, Normandy":"Amfreville, Caen, Calvados, Lower Normandy, France","Forest Vale, Redesdale, Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","Rouen, Normandy, France":"Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France","Redesdale, Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","Amfreville-sur-Iton, Departement de l'Eure, Haute-Normandie, France":"Eure, Upper Normandy, France","Normandy, France":"Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Umfreville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name from Umfreville (La Manche) or Offranville (Seine-Maritime)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"De","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert De Umfreville x Lord Tours Vian was born in 1008, in Eure, Upper Normandy, France as the son of Baroness Mary Redesdale. He had at least 3 sons with Baroness Mary Redesdale. He died in 1090, in Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France, at the age of 82, and was buried in Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France."},"et":{"1008–1090":"1008–1090","1005–1040":"1005–1040","1030–1086":"1030–1086","1092–Male":"1092–Surnud","1008":"1008","ABT 1030":"umbes 1030","1090":"1090","ABT 1086":"umbes 1086","1005":"1005","1034":"1034","1086":"1086","1030":"1030","1040":"1040","1092":"1092","Cathédrale Notre-Dame de Rouen, Rouen, Departement de la Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, France":"Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Amfreville-, Sur-Iton, Bailiwick Rouen, Normandy":"Amfreville, Caen, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Forest Vale, Redesdale, Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Rouen, Normandy, France":"Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Redesdale, Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Amfreville-sur-Iton, Departement de l'Eure, Haute-Normandie, France":"Eure, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1008–1090":"1008–1090","1005–1040":"1005–1040","1030–1086":"1030–1086","1092–Male":"1092–Kuollut","1008":"1008","ABT 1030":"noin 1030","1090":"1090","ABT 1086":"noin 1086","1005":"1005","1034":"1034","1086":"1086","1030":"1030","1040":"1040","1092":"1092","Cathédrale Notre-Dame de Rouen, Rouen, Departement de la Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, France":"